	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Not nesdev related, but interesting (we're in the general forum).<br />Do you think it's worth messing with 3D modeling in order to make better 2D graphics (such as in Donkey Kong Country) ?<br /><br />I could model simple geometric shapes with Blender, but honnestly I couldn't see how you could possibly model an human - even less how you could animate it.</div>
<br />
<br />3d models could be useful for <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotoscoping" class="postlink">rotoscoping</a> animations for some kinds of objects.  For a 3d human model, recordings from motion capture sensors seem like the way to go.
<br />
<br />So any 3d models are useless on NES alone, but I think anyone who's not a talented artist already, could always use some help with references for perspective and scale.  I've considered an approach like that for a later project.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


