	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Tue Jan 05, 2010 1:30 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Do you think it's worth messing with 3D modeling in order to make better 2D graphics (such as in Donkey Kong Country) ?</div><br />The success of Myst and Final Fantasy VII (for backgrounds) and DKC series, Toy Story, Uniracers, Super Mario RPG, and Mario vs. Donkey Kong (for sprites) says yes.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I could model simple geometric shapes with Blender, but honnestly I couldn't see how you could possibly model an human - even less how you could animate it.</div>
<br />A human starts as 19 ellipsoids: head, upper torso, lower torso, and 4 limbs. Each limb is the upper limb, lower limb, palm/sole, and a set of fingers/toes. Animate that framework and render it, and it'll look roughly like the characters from the fighting game Ballz 3D. A bit more tweaking of each ellipsoid, and you have something over which to draw a sprite sheet.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


